{{Italic title}} '''''Argumentum ad lapidem''''' ([[Latin]]: "appeal to the stone") is a [[informal fallacy|logical fallacy]] that consists in dismissing a statement as absurd without giving proof of its absurdity.<ref>[http://www.dianahsieh.com/misc/fallacies.html "Definitions of Fallacies"], Dianah Mertz Hsieh, 20 August 1995</ref><ref name="Pirie">{{cite book |title=How to win every argument: the use and abuse of logic |author=Pirie, Madsen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gh5UjNNc0v4C&lpg=PA102&dq=%22ad%20lapidem%22%20argument&pg=PA102#v=onepage&q=%22ad%20lapidem%22%20argument&f=false |pages=101–103 |isbn=978-0-8264-9006-3 |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group |date=2006}}</ref><ref name="Alexander">{{cite book |title=Collected works of Samuel Alexander |volume=4 |author=Alexander, Samuel |editor=Slater, John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5UzwJEnm3J4C&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=johnson+%22ad+lapidem%22&source=bl&ots=3s5YxwPKL3&sig=CEPVlYTIkYsngteWQpADGJt-3Us&hl=en&ei=fO_ETL-NGI3WtQOs15ztDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=johnson%20%22ad%20lapidem%22&f=false |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group |date=2000 |chapter=Dr. Johnson as a Philosopher |page=119 |isbn=978-1-85506-853-7}}</ref>
''Ad lapidem'' statements are fallacious because they fail to address the merits of the claim in dispute.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://effectiviology.com/appeal-to-the-stone-fallacy/ | title = The ‘Appeal to the Stone’ Fallacy: On Being Completely Dismissive in Arguments | last = Shatz | first = Itamar | website = Effectiviology |date= 2017}}</ref> The same applies to [[proof by assertion]], where an unproved or disproved claim is asserted as true on no ground other than that of its truth having been asserted.
The name of this fallacy is derived from a famous incident in which Dr. [[Samuel Johnson]] claimed to disprove [[Bishop Berkeley]]'s [[immaterialism|immaterialist]] philosophy (that there are no material objects, only minds and ideas in those minds) by kicking a large stone and asserting, "I refute it ''thus''."<ref name="Alexander"/> This action, which is said to fail to prove the existence of the stone outside the ideas formed by perception, is said to fail to contradict Berkeley's argument, and has been seen as merely dismissing it.<ref name="Pirie"/>
== Example == * Speaker A: [[Germ theory of disease|Infectious diseases are caused by microbes.]] * Speaker B: [[Germ theory denialism|What a ridiculous idea!]] * Speaker A: How so? * Speaker B: It's obviously ridiculous.
Speaker B gives no evidence or reasoning, and when pressed, claims that Speaker A's statement is inherently absurd, thus applying the fallacy.
