'''M. Basil Pennington''' [[Trappists|O.C.S.O.]] (1931–2005) was an American Roman Catholic [[Trappists|Trappist]] monk and priest. He was a leading spiritual writer, speaker, teacher, and director.
Pennington was an [[List of people associated with the Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas|alumnus]] of the [[Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas (Angelicum)|Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas ''Angelicum'']] where he obtained a licentiate in Theology in 1959.<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27717764 Accessed 30 August, 2013</ref> He also earned a licentiate in Canon Law at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]]. Pennington became known internationally as one of the major proponents of the [[Centering Prayer]] movement begun at [[St. Joseph's Abbey]] in [[Spencer, Massachusetts]], during the 1970s.
Pennington's book ''Centering Prayer'' was first published in 1980, and had sold more than a million copies by 2002.<ref name=garrett02>{{cite journal |author=Lynn Garrett & Jeff Zaleski |year=2002 |title=Writings of spiritual leaders. |journal=[[Publishers Weekly]] |publisher=Reed Business Information / Reviews |volume=249 |issue=43 |pages=68 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=7686947&site=ehost-live |doi= |issn= 0000-0019}}</ref><ref name=reiss02>{{cite journal |author=Jana Reiss & Jeff Zaleski |year=2002 |title=Religion notes |journal=[[Publishers Weekly]] |publisher=Reed Business Information / Reviews |volume=249 |issue=45 |pages=61 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=8497469&site=ehost-live |doi= |issn=0000-0019}}</ref><ref name=shear06>{{cite book |title=The experience of meditation: Experts introduce the major traditions |editor=Jonathan Shear |editor-link=Jonathan Shear |year= 2006 |publisher=Paragon House |location=St. Paul, MN |isbn=978-1-55778-857-3 |pages= |doi= |url= https://www.loc.gov/catdir/toc/ecip066/2005037743.html}}. On page 275: "Father Pennington helped formulate Centering Prayer... and his book ''[[Centering Prayer (book)|Centering Prayer]]'' has sold over 1 million copies throughout the world."</ref> Translations of this work have been published in Spanish,<ref name=cpspanish86>{{cite book |title=La oración centrante: renovación de una antigua manera de orar |first=M. Basil |last=Pennington |authorlink=Basil Pennington |year=1986 |publisher=Narcea |location= |isbn=978-84-277-0713-9 |page= |language=Spanish |others=(Carmen Fernández Aguinaco, trans.) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1LYpAQAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:Basil+inauthor:Pennington&hl=en&ei=KmoyTIbzHcSFnQes0snhAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA |accessdate=}} (235 pages)</ref> French,<ref name=cpfrench06>{{cite book |title=La prière de silence: Renouveler une forme traditionnelle de prière chrétienne |first=M. Basil |last=Pennington |authorlink=Basil Pennington |year=2006 |publisher=Novalis |others=(Bernard Dionne, trans.) |location= |language=French |isbn=978-2-89507-684-1 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LRXcPQAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:Basil+inauthor:Pennington&hl=en&ei=G20yTJPhEursnQeV8dHXAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA |accessdate=}} (261 pages)</ref> Polish,<ref name=cppolish03>{{cite book |title=Modlitwa prowadząca do środka: Powrót do starochrześcijańskiej metody modlitwy |first=M. Basil |last=Pennington |authorlink=Basil Pennington |year=2003 |publisher=Homini |others= |location= |language=Polish |isbn=978-83-87933-91-3 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uRDdAQAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:Basil+inauthor:Pennington&hl=en&ei=aXAyTNCOD5WEnQeugbXlAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA |accessdate=}} (280 pages)</ref> Portuguese,<ref name=cpportuguese02>{{cite book |title=Oração Centrante |first=M. Basil |last=Pennington |authorlink=Basil Pennington |year=2002 |publisher=Palas Athena |others= |location= |language=Portuguese |isbn=978-85-7242-041-9 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_6bbQgAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:basil+inauthor:Pennington&hl=en&ei=vXIyTMvqOIOgnweDtcXbAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA |accessdate=}} (296 pages)</ref> and Italian.<ref name=cpitalian07>{{cite book |title=Preghiera centrica |first=M. Basil |last=Pennington |authorlink=Basil Pennington |year=2007 |publisher=Gribaudi |others= |location= |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-7152-903-5 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcSYPAAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:basil+inauthor:Pennington&hl=en&ei=1nQyTLDoL5WNnQeK7qTgAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ |accessdate=}}</ref>
==Life==
Pennington entered the [[Trappists|Order of Cistercians of the Strict Observance]] at St. Joseph's Abbey in June 1951. At St. Joseph's Abbey, he was appointed professor of theology in 1959, professor of canon law and professor of spirituality in 1963, and vocation director in 1978. In 2000, he was appointed superior at [[Assumption Abbey, Missouri|Assumption Abbey]] in [[Ava, Missouri]], and later that same year, he was elected abbot of the [[Monastery of the Holy Spirit]] in [[Conyers, Georgia]]. He returned to St. Joseph's Abbey after retiring in 2002. He died on June 3, 2005, the [[Feast of the Sacred Heart|Feast of the Sacred Heart of Jesus]], from injuries sustained from a car accident.
[[Bernard McGinn (theologian)|Bernard McGinn]] wrote that Pennington "not only wrote effectively about centering prayer, but he also traveled across the United States and the world spreading the practice through lectures and workshops. The renewal of contemplative prayer in the last decades of the twentieth century owes much to these efforts."<ref name=mcginn06>{{cite journal |author=[[Bernard McGinn (theologian)|Bernard McGinn]] |year=2006 |title=Let us now praise... M. Basil Pennington, OCSO (1931-2005) |journal=[[Theology Today]] |publisher= |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=96–99 |url= |doi= |issn=0040-5736 |oclc=1587753}}</ref>{{rp|98}}
In Pennington's obituary, McGinn stated that "For those who never met Basil Pennington, reading the published form of the journal he kept during [a visit to [[Mount Athos]]<ref name=holymountain>M. Basil Pennington, O Holy Mountain! Journal of a Retreat on Mount Athos (Garden City, NY: Doubleday, 1978)</ref>] will provide a good sense of the man in all his humanity and irrepressible goodwill."<ref name=mcginn06/>{{rp|98}}
