{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | era = [[19th-century philosophy]] | name = David George Ritchie | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1853 | birth_place = [[Jedburgh]] | death_date = 1903 | death_place = | alma_mater = [[University of Edinburgh]] | institutions = | school_tradition = [[British idealism]] | main_interests = [[Ethics]] | notable_ideas = | influences = [[Thomas Hill Green]] | influenced = }} '''David George Ritchie''' (1853–1903) was a Scottish philosopher who had a distinguished university career at [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]], and [[Balliol College, Oxford]], and after being [[fellow]] of [[Jesus College, Oxford|Jesus College]] and a tutor at [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]] was elected professor of logic and metaphysics at [[university of St Andrews|St Andrews]]. He was also the third president of the [[Aristotelian Society]] in 1898.
==Life== [[File:The grave of Prof David George Ritchie, Eastern Cemetery, St Andrews.jpg|thumb|The grave of Prof David George Ritchie, Eastern Cemetery, St Andrews]] Ritchie was born at [[Jedburgh]] on 26 October 1853. He was the only son of the three children of George Ritchie, D.D., minister of the parish and a man of scholarship and culture, who was elected to the office of moderator of the general assembly of the [[Church of Scotland]] in 1870. His mother was Elizabeth Bradfute Dudgeon. The family was connected with the [[Thomas Carlyle|Carlyles]], and early in 1889 Ritchie edited a volume of ''Early Letters of [[Jane Welsh Carlyle]].''{{sfn|Haldane|1912}}
Ritchie received his early schooling at Jedburgh Academy. Not allowed to make friends with other boys of his own age, he never learned to play games, and lived a solitary life, concentrating his mind on purely intellectual subjects. He matriculated in 1869 at [[Edinburgh University]], where he made a special study of classics under Professors [[William Young Sellar]] and [[John Stuart Blackie|J. S. Blackie]], while he began to study philosophy under Professor Campbell Fraser, in whose class and in that of Professor [[Henry Calderwood]] (on moral philosophy) he gained the highest prizes. After graduating M.A. at Edinburgh in 1875 with first-class honours in classics, Ritchie gained a classical exhibition at [[Balliol College, Oxford]], and won a first-class both in classical moderations (Michaelmas 1875) and in the final classical school (Trinity term, 1878). In 1878 he became a fellow of [[Jesus College, Oxford]] and in 1881 a tutor. From 1882 to 1886 he was also a tutor at Balliol College. At Oxford Ritchie came under the influence of [[Thomas Hill Green]] and [[Arnold Toynbee]], and it was there that the foundations were laid both for his interest in idealistic philosophy associated with the name of [[G. W. F. Hegel]] (see [[British idealism]]), and also of his strong bent toward practical politics; his political philosophy was dominated by the belief that practical action must be derived from principles.{{sfn|Haldane|1912}}
Ritchie married twice. His first marriage was in 1881 to Flora Lindsay, daughter of Col. A. A. Macdonell of Lochgarry, and sister of Professor A. A. Macdonell of Oxford. Flora died in 1888. He was married a second time in 1889 to Ellen Haycraft, sister of [[John Berry Haycraft|Professor John Berry Haycraft]]. He had a daughter by the first marriage and a son, [[Arthur David Ritchie]], by the second.{{sfn|Haldane|1912}}
In 1894 Ritchie left Oxford on being appointed professor of logic and metaphysics at the [[University of St. Andrews]]. At this time the university was in the midst of a turmoil of conflicting interests which involved litigation and much partisan feeling. In this conflict Ritchie supported the side of progress, which ultimately prevailed.
D. G. Ritchie was a founding member, and the third President (1898–1899), of the [[Aristotelian Society]], an influential academic organisation that is still very much in active existence.
He remained at St. Andrews until his death on 3 February 1903.{{sfn|Haldane|1912}} He is buried in the north-east corner of the Eastern Cemetery in [[St Andrews]] beneath a large black granite cross.
==Philosophy== Both at Oxford and at St. Andrews, Ritchie wrote mostly on ethics and political philosophy. One of his earliest writings was an essay on ''The Rationality of History,'' contributed to [https://archive.org/details/essaysinphilosop00sethrich ''Essays in Philosophical Criticism,''] written in 1883 by a number of young men influenced by Hegel and his interpreters. He was very much one of the generation of thinkers who were sometimes referred to as the '''Young Hegelians'''.
Of a simple and unaffected nature, Ritchie pursued the truth he set himself to seek with an entire devotion. Despite his retiring manner, he had many friends. He held strongly that questions of ethics and politics must be regarded from a metaphysical point of view. For him the foundation of ethics necessarily rested on the ideal end of social well-being, and keeping this end in view, he proceeded to trace its history at different times, the manner in which it shapes itself in the mind of each individual, and the way in which it can be developed and realised. Ritchie was an advanced liberal with socialist leanings. He considered that the ultimate value of religion depended on the ideal it set before mankind when it represented its highest form.{{sfn|Haldane|1912}}
==Works== Among his works may be cited: *[https://archive.org/details/cu31924030242618 ''Darwinism and Politics''] (1889) *[https://archive.org/details/principlesstate00ritcgoog ''Principles of State Interference: Four Essays on the Political Philosophy of Mr Herbert Spencer, J S Mill, and T H Green''] (1891) *[https://archive.org/details/darwinhegelwitho00ritcrich ''Darwin and Hegel''] (1893) *[https://archive.org/details/naturalrightscri00ritcuoft ''Natural Rights''] (1895) *[https://archive.org/details/studiesinpoliti00ritcuoft ''Studies in Political and Social Ethics''] (1902) *[https://archive.org/details/platodav00ritc ''Plato''] (1902) *A translation with [[Sir Richard Lodge]] and [[Percy Ewing Matheson]] of [[Bluntschli]]'s [https://archive.org/details/theorystate01lodggoog ''Theory of the State''] (1885) *Many articles in the philosophical journal [[Mind (journal)|Mind]], the ''Philosophical Review'', etc.
His [https://archive.org/details/philosophicalstu00ritciala ''Philosophical Studies''] was edited with a memoir by Robert Latta (1905).
