{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Ethics of Liberty | image = TheEthicsofLiberty.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = Paperback cover | author = [[Murray N. Rothbard]] | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Ethics]], [[political philosophy]] | published = {{plainlist| * 1982 ([[Humanities Press]]) * 1998 ([[New York University Press]]) }} | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] & [[Paperback]]) & [[e-book]], audio-CD | pages = 336 (Online e–book edition) | isbn = 0-391-02371-3 | isbn_note = (Paperback edition) | dewey= 323.44/01 19 | congress= JC585 .R69 1982 | oclc= 7813705 }}
'''''The Ethics of Liberty''''' is a 1982 book by American [[philosophy|philosopher]] and [[economics|economist]] [[Murray N. Rothbard]]; in it, Rothbard expounds a libertarian political position.
==Summary== Rothbard provides an exposition of the [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] political position. He argues for the case of [[Freedom (political)|freedom]] as a concept of [[natural rights]] and applies it to a variety of practical problems.
==Reception==
Reception of the book has been positive in libertarian circles. Many praise the book for its incisive analysis of [[natural law]] and its practical applications. Libertarian commentator Sheldon Richman says : "''The Ethics of Liberty'' is a great book that deserves the attention of anyone interested in the good society and human flourishing."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fff.org/explore-freedom/article/tgif-rothbards-the-ethics-of-liberty-still-worthy-after-all-these-years/|title=TGIF: Rothbard’s The Ethics of Liberty: Still Worthy after All These Years - The Future of Freedom Foundation|website=fff.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>
[[Hans-Hermann Hoppe]], who wrote the introduction to later editions of the book, described ''The Ethics of Liberty'' as Murray Rothbard's second [[masterpiece|magnum opus]], the other being ''[[Man, Economy, and State]]'' (1962).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mises.org/rothbard/ethics/hoppeintro.asp|title=The Ethics of Liberty {{!}} Murray N. Rothbard|last=kanopiadmin|date=2014-08-18|work=Mises Institute|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref>
[[University of San Diego]] [[philosophy]] [[professor]] Matt Zwolinski criticized the book, writing that Rothbard's [[Conversation|discussion]] of [[self-ownership]] in chapter six "rests on a fundamental confusion between descriptive and normative claims."<ref>{{cite web|last=Zwolinski|first=Matt|url=http://bleedingheartlibertarians.com/2012/10/reading-the-ethics-of-liberty-part-4-rothbards-second-argument-for-self-ownership/|title=rothbards-second-argument-for-self-ownership|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>
==Release history== * [[New York University Press]]. New York, N.Y. February 1, 2003. Paperback. {{ISBN|0-8147-7559-4}} * New York [[University]] Press. New York, N.Y. May 1, 1998. Hardcover. {{ISBN|0-8147-7506-3}} * [[Humanities Press]]. Atlantic Highlands, N.J. 1982. Hardcover. {{ISBN|0-391-02371-3}}
